11. Patents.

A "contributor" is a copyright holder who authorizes use under this
License of the contributor's work.

A contributor's "essential patent claims" are all patent claims
owned or controlled by the contributor, whether already acquired or

hereafter acquired, that would be infringed by some manner, permitted
by this License, of making, using, or selling its contribution,

excluding claims that would be infringed only as a consequence of
combining the contribution with the work to which the contribution was
made.

Each contributor grants you a non-exclusive, worldwide, royalty-free
patent license under the contributor's essential patent claims, to
make, use, sell, offer for sale, import and otherwise run, modify and
propagate the contents of its contributor version.

In the following three paragraphs, a "patent license" is any express
agreement or commitment, however denominated, not to enforce a patent
against

conduct permitted by this License. If you convey a covered work, you
prominently offer each recipient a patent license covering the
recipient's use of the work, or you convey the work under terms that

substantially reciprocate the patent license that applies to the
contributor's version.

If you convey a covered work, knowingly relying on a patent license,
and the Corresponding Source of the work is not available for anyone

to copy, free of charge and under the terms of this License, then you
must either cause the Corresponding Source to be so available, or
provide a copy of the Corresponding Source along with the object code.

If you convey a covered work and grant a patent license to some of the
recipients, then the patent license you grant is automatically
expanded to all recipients of the covered work and works based on it.

A patent license is "discriminatory" if it does not include within the
scope of its coverage, prohibits the exercise of, or is conditioned on
the non-exercise of one or more of the rights that are specifically
granted under this License. You may not convey a covered work if you
are a party to an agreement with a third party that is in whole or in
part
an express condition that is discriminatory with respect to the
covered work.

If you convey a covered work, and at the same time convey a separate
patent license to some of the recipients of the covered work, then the
patent license is considered "discriminatory" if it does not permit

those recipients to exercise all the rights granted under this
License. If such a discriminatory patent license is offered, the
recipient automatically receives a license to exercise the rights
granted by this License to the extent necessary to make use of the
covered work.

Notwithstanding any other provision of this License, you may also
convey a covered work under terms of another license that is
compatible with this License, provided that the other license
explicitly permits public disclosure of the source code and does not
impose any additional restrictions beyond those of this License.

